Here's an example of how you might use `useCallback`:

```jsx
import { useCallback, useState } from 'react';

function MyComponent() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  // Create a memoized version of the increment function
  const increment = useCallback(() => {
    setCount(count + 1);
  }, [count]);

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Count: {count}</p>
      <button onClick={increment}>Increment</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

In this example, the `increment` function is only recreated when the `count` state changes. This is because we've included `count` in the dependency array of `useCallback`.

